Autonomous_Vehicles_SVHN_single Project

Problem Statement¶

Context¶

Part A: A communications equipment manufacturing company wants to build a machine learning model to predict the signal quality of their product, which emits informative signals, using various parameters.

Part B: Recognizing multi-digit numbers in photographs captured at street level is crucial for modern map making. Google's Street View imagery is a prime example. This project focuses on building a digit classifier on the SVHN (Street View Housing Number) dataset, using images centered around a single digit, which is more complex than MNIST due to distractors.

Objective¶

Part A: To build a classifier that can use given parameters to determine the signal strength or quality.

Part B: To build a digit classifier on the SVHN (Street View Housing Number) dataset.

Data Description¶

Part A:

  • Parameters: Various measurable signal parameters.
  • Signal_Quality: Final signal strength or quality.

Part B:

  • SVHN Dataset: A real-world image dataset obtained from house numbers in Google Street View images.
  • Images: Images centered around a single digit, with some distractors.
  • Labels: The prominent number in each image (e.g., 2, 6, 7, 4).
  • Format: Dataset provided in h5py files.

Part A - Q3 A - Design a Neural Network to train a classifier.¶

In [39]:
from tensorflow.keras import layers

# Define the neural network model
model = keras.Sequential([
    layers.Dense(1024, activation='relu', input_shape=(X_vtrain_scaled.shape[1],)),  # Input layer
    layers.BatchNormalization(),  # Normalize activations
    layers.Dropout(0.3),  # Reduce overfitting
    layers.Dense(512, activation='relu'),
    layers.BatchNormalization(),
    layers.Dropout(0.3),
    layers.Dense(256, activation='relu'),
    layers.BatchNormalization(),
    layers.Dropout(0.3),
    layers.Dense(len(set(y_vtrain_encoded)), activation='softmax')  # Output layer with softmax for classification
])

# Compile the model with Adam optimizer and sparse categorical cross-entropy loss
model.compile(optimizer=keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.0001),
              loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics=['accuracy'])

# Display model architecture
model.summary()

Improved Learning Capacity in Model1¶

  • The deeper architecture of Model1 with larger layer sizes and more neurons allows it to capture more complex patterns in the data.
  • The training accuracy of Model1 improves more steadily compared to Model, suggesting that it benefits from the increased depth.

Overfitting Concerns in Model1¶

  • The validation accuracy of Model1 shows some fluctuations, which could indicate slight overfitting.
  • This might be due to the larger number of parameters, making the model more prone to memorizing the training data.

Effect of Dropout and Batch Normalization¶

  • Model1 has a higher dropout rate (0.4) compared to Model (0.3), which helps in regularization.
  • The addition of batch normalization in both models stabilizes training, but Model1 benefits more due to its increased complexity.

Learning Rate Adjustment¶

  • Model1 uses a higher learning rate (0.0003) than Model (0.0001), helping it learn faster, but it may also cause instability in validation performance.

Conclusion¶

  • Model1 outperforms Model in terms of training accuracy and overall learning capacity.
  • However, Model1 has a risk of overfitting as seen in validation fluctuations.
  • Further fine-tuning with early stopping or learning rate scheduling could help improve generalization.

model1 = keras.Sequential([
    layers.Dense(2560, activation='relu', input_shape=(X_vtrain_scaled.shape[1],)),
    layers.BatchNormalization(),
    layers.Dropout(0.4),

    layers.Dense(1280, activation='relu'),
    layers.BatchNormalization(),
    layers.Dropout(0.4),

    layers.Dense(640, activation='relu'),
    layers.BatchNormalization(),
    layers.Dropout(0.4),

    layers.Dense(320, activation='relu'),
    layers.BatchNormalization(),
    layers.Dropout(0.4),

    layers.Dense(len(set(y_vtrain_encoded)), activation='softmax')
])

# Compile and Train
model1.compile(optimizer=keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.0003),
              loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

Observations and Insights¶

1. Loss Comparison¶

  • Model 1 (blue) starts with a higher loss but decreases over time.
  • Model 2 (red) has a lower initial loss and decreases faster, suggesting better initial learning.
  • However, Model 2's validation loss starts increasing after ~60 epochs, indicating overfitting.
  • Model 1’s validation loss stabilizes but remains higher.

2. Accuracy Comparison¶

  • Model 2 achieves higher training accuracy than Model 1.
  • Validation accuracy for Model 2 stagnates after ~60 epochs, indicating overfitting.
  • Model 1 has a smoother validation accuracy curve but does not reach as high as Model 2.
  • Model 2 generalizes poorly compared to its training performance.

Key Takeaways¶

  • Model 2 learns faster but overfits more.
  • Model 1 is more stable but learns slower.
  • To improve generalization, techniques like early stopping or regularization can be used.

Part B - Q3 A - Design a Neural Network to train a classifier.¶

In [62]:
# Designing Neural Network  Architechture and training the neural network with the training dataset

def neural_network_model():

  backend.clear_session()
  #Fixing the seed for random number generators so that we can ensure we receive the same output everytime
  random.seed(42)
  tf.random.set_seed(42)

  model= Sequential()
  model.add(BatchNormalization(input_shape=((1024,))))
  model.add(Dense(256,activation='relu'))
  model.add(Dense(64,activation='relu'))
  model.add(Dense(32,activation='relu'))
  model.add(Dense(10,activation='softmax'))

  # compile the model

  sgd = optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=1e-3)  # Corrected line
  model.compile(loss=losses.categorical_crossentropy,optimizer=sgd,metrics=['accuracy'])
  return model

from tensorflow.keras.backend import clear_session

random.seed(42)
tf.random.set_seed(42)

# Define the improved neural network model
def neural_network_model():
    clear_session()  # Clears memory ✅ FIXED

    model = Sequential([
        BatchNormalization(input_shape=(1024,)),  # Input Normalization
        Dense(256, activation='relu'),
        Dropout(0.3),  # Prevent Overfitting
        Dense(128, activation='relu'),
        Dropout(0.2),
        Dense(64, activation='relu'),
        Dense(10, activation='softmax')  # 10 output classes
    ])

    # Adam optimizer with reduced learning rate
    adam_optimizer = optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=5e-4)

    # Compile model
    model.compile(loss=losses.categorical_crossentropy, optimizer=adam_optimizer, metrics=['accuracy'])

    return model

Observations from Training & Validation Plots¶

Training vs. Validation Loss¶

  • Both losses decrease, indicating good learning.
  • Validation loss is lower than training loss, possibly due to regularization (dropout, batch normalization).
  • Loss stabilizes after ~60 epochs, showing diminishing improvements.

Training vs. Validation Accuracy¶

  • Accuracy improves steadily, reaching ~90% validation accuracy.
  • Validation accuracy is slightly higher than training, likely due to batch normalization effects.

Key Insights¶

  • The model generalizes well with no signs of severe overfitting.
  • Validation performing better than training suggests possible batch norm or dropout effects.
  • Further tuning dropout or batch size might slightly enhance training accuracy.
